Zhang Guangjun was appointed deputy governor of Guangdong Province.
The fifth session of the Standing Committee of the 13th Guangdong Provincial People&#39;s Congress held its second plenary session in Guangzhou on the 30th.
The meeting voted and decided to appoint Zhang Guangjun as deputy governor of the Guangdong Provincial People&#39;s Government.
Previously, Zhang Guangjun served as deputy secretary of the Party Committee of the China Institute of Engineering Physics.
Resume of Comrade Zhang Guangjun: Zhang Guangjun, male, Han nationality, born in February 1968, Chongqing native, joined the Party in April 1994, started working in July 1991, graduated from the Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin Institute of Technology, majoring in electronic instruments and measurement technology, university degree, senior Engineer, expert enjoying special government allowance from the State Council.
He currently serves as deputy governor and member of the leading party group of the Guangdong Provincial Government.
From 1987 to 1991, studied electronic instruments and measurement technology in the Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin Institute of Technology
1991-1998 Technician of General Engineering Research Institute of China Academy of Engineering Physics, Deputy Director of the Office, Secretary and Deputy Director of the Party Branch of the Office
1998-2002 Deputy Director of the General Engineering Research Institute and Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during this period: 1999.05-2000.12 concurrently served as Secretary of the Institute&#39;s Discipline Inspection Commission, 2001.09-2001.12 studied in the advanced training class for prefecture-level cadres at the Party School of the Sichuan Provincial Committee)
2002-2002 Secretary of the Party Committee and Deputy Director of the General Engineering Research Institute of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during the period: 2002.03-2004.05 studied in the postgraduate course of the management science and engineering major of the School of Management, Fudan University)
2002-2009 Director of the Political Department of the China Institute of Engineering Physics, Director of the Party Committee Office, and Vice President of the Party School (during the period: 2005.09-2006.01 studied in the training class for young and middle-aged cadres of the Central Party School)
2009-2014 Director of the Major Project Management Office of China Institute of Engineering Physics (during the period: 2011.09-2012.01 studied in the training class for young and middle-aged cadres of the Central Party School)
2014-2015 Assistant to the President of the China Academy of Engineering Physics and Director of the Major Project Management Office
2015-2018 Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of China Institute of Engineering Physics
In September 2018, he was appointed as deputy governor and member of the leading party group of the Guangdong Provincial Government.
According to British media, Adm. William Moran, the U.S. Deputy Chief of Naval Operations, said that even as the U.S. Navy is revitalizing its strength to deal with increasingly worrying Russia on both sides of the Atlantic, the United States continues to focus on the Asia-Pacific region - the Pentagon is focusing on the region The scope is expanded to include the Indo-Asia-Pacific -- as the Navy&#39;s focus.
According to a report on the British &quot;Jane&#39;s Defense Weekly&quot; website on September 24, the United States listed China and Russia as strategic competitors in the new national defense strategy announced at the beginning of the year.
The U.S. Navy has since reinstated its Second Fleet to more directly counter Russian activities.
According to reports, these moves have caused some doubts and concerns among allies and analysts, who worry that the U.S. Navy may move away from the &quot;Rebalancing to Asia-Pacific&quot; strategy that marked the Obama administration.
But Admiral Moran said the U.S. Navy&#39;s focus remains on the Western Pacific.
&quot;For us, there have been no significant changes,&quot; he said at a roundtable discussion titled &quot;Responding to the Challenge of the High Seas&quot; hosted by the National Bureau of Asian Research in Washington on January 24, 2018.
&quot;The emphasis remains on rebalancing, shifting focus or however you want to describe it,&quot; Moran said.
However, he acknowledged that the United States has close relations with Europe.
&quot;We&#39;re going to continue to focus on growth on the West Coast and balance what we can do,&quot; he said.
While Moran noted that overall policy regarding Russia falls within the purview of the U.S. secretary of defense, he warned: &quot;The Russians may face demographic and economic challenges, but history has proven that if we conflict with them, they will be very tough. &quot;
Admiral Moran said that as part of the U.S. comeback campaign against Russia, China and other competitors, the U.S. Navy is dynamically deploying forces into a &quot;new operating model&quot; that will help adversaries fight U.S. aircraft carriers. Unprepared for where swarms or other assets will be deployed at any given time and place.
&quot;We in the Navy and Marine Corps support it -- the concept of operational unpredictability, not being in the same place over and over again, almost like clockwork -- that&#39;s our approach,&quot; he said.
According to reports, the first to try this new approach was the &quot;Harry Truman&quot; aircraft carrier strike group. The early deployment of the strike group included working visits to ports and patrols in areas that were usually only passed through.
Moran said the Navy is currently working to ensure allies know the ships will still patrol traditional areas and is also working out logistics and family liaison issues for the new deployment process.
Vice Admiral Michael Noonan, commander of the Royal Australian Navy, also spoke at the event, saying that the Australian military can cooperate seamlessly with the US aircraft carrier battle group.
He said this would continue as the Royal Australian Navy plans to acquire nine more frigates equipped with the Aegis combat system.
Starting from October 5th, many airlines will increase or resume fuel surcharges. From next Friday, you will have to pay more for air travel.
Yesterday, Lucky Air, Okay Airways and other airlines announced that starting from October 5, 2018 (ticket issuance date), each passenger will be charged a fuel surcharge of 20 yuan for domestic routes with a fuel surcharge of less than 800 kilometers (inclusive). , each passenger on routes over 800 kilometers will be charged a fuel surcharge of 30 yuan.
Lucky Air, Okay Airways and other companies announced that starting from 0:00 on October 5, 2018 (ticket issuance date), the fuel surcharge standard for domestic routes below 800 kilometers (inclusive) will increase from 10 yuan/person to 20 yuan/person. , the fuel surcharge standard for domestic routes over 800 kilometers increased from 10 yuan per passenger to 30 yuan per person.
Children, military, police and disabled people are charged 10 yuan per person; infants continue to be exempted.
According to the person in charge of Ctrip air tickets, the airline has stated in the notice that the fuel surcharge will be charged based on the original ticket issuance date. When the ticket is reissued, the fuel surcharge will not be refunded or reimbursed.
This means that if domestic route tickets issued before October 5th are changed to after October 5th (inclusive), they do not need to pay the fuel surcharge according to the new standard.
Since June 5, 2018, Air China, China Eastern Airlines, Hainan Airlines, Shanghai Airlines, Spring Airlines, Shenzhen Airlines, West Air, Okay Airways and many other airlines have resumed charging domestic route fuel surcharges that have been canceled for three years. The charging standard is 10 yuan/person.
This time, Lucky Air and Okay Airways took the lead in announcing an increase in fuel surcharges. As of press time, there has been no news of follow-up adjustments from the four major domestic airlines.
It is also understood that the Hong Kong Civil Aviation Department stipulates that airlines can decide whether to charge fuel surcharges starting from November.
Cathay Pacific first announced on September 27 that it would resume collecting fuel surcharges from November 2.
The Cathay Pacific website shows that all tickets issued or reissued by Cathay Pacific and Cathay Dragon on or after November 2 will include fuel surcharges for long-distance travel between Hong Kong and the Southwest Pacific, North America, Europe, the Middle East and India, and Africa. For flights, the fuel surcharge is 652 yuan, while for short-haul flights, the fuel surcharge is 146 yuan.
Fees apply to all ticket types, are calculated on a per-segment basis, and include airfare quotes on all Cathay Pacific direct sales channels.
On the eve of the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People&#39;s Republic of China, Chinese Premier Li Keqiang met with newly-appointed envoys to China from 29 countries and regions at the Great Hall of the People on the afternoon of the 30th.
Li Keqiang shook hands and had cordial conversations with all the envoys stationed in China.
Li Keqiang welcomed the envoys to China to take up their new posts and asked them to convey his sincere greetings and best wishes to the leaders and people of relevant countries and leaders of relevant institutions.
Li Keqiang spoke positively of China&#39;s good relations with other countries and regions, stressing that China is committed to enhancing bilateral political mutual trust, deepening practical cooperation, and strengthening coordination and cooperation in international and regional affairs. He hoped that the envoys would travel more and see more, and be in the new era. In this position, he has made new and positive contributions to promoting the development of relations between China and other countries and regions.
The Chinese government is willing to provide convenience and support for the envoys to perform their duties.
Li Keqiang pointed out that China adheres to the path of peaceful development and unswervingly promotes economic globalization.
This year marks the 40th anniversary of China&#39;s reform and opening up. As the world&#39;s largest developing country, we are willing to achieve common development with other countries in further opening up.
Against the background of rising protectionism and unilateralism, we are willing to work with all parties to continue to consolidate and strengthen partnerships based on the principles of mutual respect, equality and mutual benefit, promote the docking of development strategies, and promote the development of China in the spirit of the principle of extensive consultation, joint contribution and shared benefits. Cooperate in the construction of the &quot;Belt and Road&quot;, work together to defend multilateralism and free trade, jointly build an open world economy, and inject new impetus into promoting stable and balanced development of the world economy.
The envoys of various countries and institutions in China warmly congratulated the 69th anniversary of the founding of the People&#39;s Republic of China, conveyed the greetings of the leaders of their respective countries and institutions to the Chinese leaders and people, and expressed that China has made outstanding achievements in development and believes that further deepening of reform and opening up in the future will bring great benefits to the Chinese people. The world brings more development opportunities.
We are willing to play an active role in promoting friendly cooperation between our respective countries and regions and China and better achieving mutual benefit and win-win results.
Subsequently, envoys from various countries and institutions in China attended the National Day reception at the invitation of Li Keqiang.
State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi attended the event.
Japan&#39;s Itochu Corporation recognized an impairment loss of US$1.3 billion on its investment in China&#39;s CITIC Holdings on Friday, writing down its largest corporate investment transaction due to the impact of trade tensions between China and the United States.
In May 2016, a man walked past the headquarters of Marubeni Corporation in Tokyo, Japan.
Marubeni said that the trade war has impacted its U.S. grain unit, Koh Hung, and it has suspended financial transactions in agriculture.
Some Japanese heavy equipment manufacturers, telecommunications companies, etc. have previously warned about the impact of Sino-US trade friction when announcing their latest results. Now these Japanese trading companies have also joined the ranks.
The United States and China have imposed tariffs on hundreds of billions of dollars of each other&#39;s goods, and U.S. President Trump has threatened to expand the scope of the tariffs to all more than $500 billion of Chinese goods exported to the United States if the dispute cannot be resolved.
Tsuyoshi Hachimura, Chief Financial Officer of Itochu Corporation, said that the impact of the trade dispute on the Chinese economy may be greater next year.
Itochu Corporation and Thailand&#39;s Charoen Pokphand Group invested US$10 billion in CITIC in 2015, acquiring 20% of its equity.
Hachimura said Itochu had booked a 143.3 billion yen ($1.3 billion) loss on this part of the holding because it believed CITIC&#39;s share price would not rebound in the near future.
Itochu Corporation maintained its profit forecast for the fiscal year ending March 31, 2019 at 500 billion yen.
China imposed a 25% import tariff on U.S. soybeans in July in retaliation for Washington&#39;s moves in trade friction.
&quot;Our grain business has been hit by the U.S.-China trade friction,&quot; said Marubeni Chief Financial Officer Nobuhiro Yabe.
He said that Gao Hong has stopped financial transactions in his account since September.
Gaohong spokesman Pat Burke said in a statement on Friday that the company&#39;s move was &quot;in accordance with internal policy restrictions and due to a lack of market opportunity.&quot;
He also said the suspension of financial transactions would not result in a loss of jobs.
Marubeni kept its annual profit forecast of 230 billion yen unchanged, helped by its pulp and paper and power generation businesses.
Sumitomo Corporation on Thursday reported a 16% profit increase from April to September, emphasizing that &quot;the trade issues between the United States and China have led to an uncertain outlook.&quot;
Mitsubishi Corp on Friday raised its annual profit forecast to a record level, citing rising coking coal production and rising commodity prices such as oil and coal.
Mitsubishi Corporation also announced a new business plan, striving to increase profits to 900 billion yen (US$7.98 billion) in the fiscal year ending March 31, 2022, from this year&#39;s estimated 640 billion yen.
