People&#39;s Daily Online, Beijing, November 5 (Wang Xiaoyan) Under the current wave of &quot;mass entrepreneurship and innovation&quot;, more and more technology companies have begun to pay attention to patent research and development and related protection work, deeply explore the potential value of patents, and occupy the market. Dominance.
Similarly, many technology companies have encountered considerable infringement incidents in terms of patent technology licensing and patent technology use.
At the end of 2017, Tan Wei, He Zhanghong, and Lai Bin from Guangdong Province filed a lawsuit against Beijing Xiaoju Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Xiaoju Technology), the developer of the &quot;Didi Chuxing&quot; APP, and Didi Chuxing, the operator, on the grounds of patent infringement. Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Didi Chuxing) and the seller Guangdong Pacific Internet Information Services Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Guangdong Pacific) sued the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court.
The three plaintiffs requested the court to order the three defendants to immediately stop manufacturing, selling, offering to sell, and using the plaintiff&#39;s patent.
On October 30, 2018, the China Judgment Documents Network published the &quot;First-instance Civil Ruling on the Invention Patent Infringement Dispute between Tan Wei, He Zhanghong, et al. and Beijing Xiaoju Technology Co., Ltd.&quot;, which disclosed the parts of the Didi Chuxing APP that were accused of patent infringement. Case details.
The three plaintiffs believe that the patentee and inventor of the &quot;mobile terminal-based carpooling service system and method&quot; patent, and that the entire operation process of the &quot;Hitchhiking&quot; application in the &quot;Didi Chuxing&quot; APP corresponds to the technical solution protected by the patent involved, constitutes patent infringement.
However, during the court ruling, Xiaoju Technology believed that Guangdong Pacific was not a qualified defendant. It only provided free downloads of the involved APP &quot;Didi Chuxing&quot; on the Internet and did not implement the patent method involved. There was no direct or indirect infringement. behavior and should not be named as a defendant in this case.
Secondly, the place of infringement in this case is not in Guangdong.
According to legal provisions, the place of infringement of the patent involved in the case should be the place where the patented method involved in the case is completely implemented. Therefore, the court raised an objection to the jurisdiction and requested that the case be transferred to the court where the defendant is domiciled, that is, the Beijing Intellectual Property Court.
The Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court held that the defendant Guangdong Pacific provided the allegedly infringing Didi Chuxing APP product on its online platform, and it was not inappropriate for the plaintiff to name the defendant Guangdong Pacific as a defendant.
Moreover, the defendant Guangdong Pacific&#39;s domicile is in Guangzhou City, which is within the jurisdiction of the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court.
The defendant Xiaoju Technology Co., Ltd. advocated that the case be transferred to the Beijing Intellectual Property Court for trial. However, due to insufficient basis, the defendant Xiaoju Technology Co., Ltd. rejected the objection to the jurisdiction of the case and bore the costs of accepting the jurisdiction objection case.
At present, other trial status of the case has not been announced, and reporters will also pay close attention to the subsequent details of Didi Chuxing’s patent infringement case.
Exclusive interview with the CEO of the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization: Australia-China scientific and technological cooperation has achieved remarkable results
&quot;China&#39;s science and technology have developed rapidly in the past few decades, and Australia and China can achieve fruitful results by working together in the scientific field. &quot;
Larry Marshall, CEO of the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization, said in an exclusive interview with a reporter from China News Service in Beijing that from addressing climate change to cooperation on the &quot;Eye in the Sky&quot; project, Australia-China cooperation in the field of science and technology is showing great vitality.
As the largest national scientific research institution in the Australian Commonwealth, CSIRO has achieved many innovative research results that have attracted world attention in the fields of oceans, energy, biology, materials, astronomy and other fields.
CSIRO has maintained close cooperative relations with scientific research institutions such as the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
&quot;This is an enduring friendship that embodies trust in partners and a tradition of long-term cooperation,&quot; Marshall said.
In May this year, China&#39;s 500-meter spherical radio telescope - &quot;China Sky Eye&quot; installed the world&#39;s first 19-beam L-band receiver.
This 19-beam feed receiver, currently the most advanced in the world, was jointly developed by Chinese and Australian scientists.
Marshall said that the successful development of the receiver is based on CSIRO’s years of technological accumulation. After its launch, the FAST survey speed will be increased by 5 to 6 times, and at the same time, it will also expand more scientific observation targets.
&quot;This is CSIRO&#39;s contribution to FAST. &quot;
In addition to the above-mentioned cooperation, CSIRO also has close cooperation with Chinese scientific research institutions in the construction of square kilometer array radio telescopes, research and development of new fuel technologies, energy conservation and emission reduction.
&quot;Previous scientific research often focused on problems hundreds of years in the future, but now more scientific research power is needed to solve the problems in front of us. &quot;
Marshall believes that Australia and China are complementary in the field of scientific development, and at the same time, both countries face a series of challenges in their development.
For example, extreme weather occurs frequently around the world. Droughts and floods have led to reduced food production. Food shortages have seriously affected human development.
At the same time, issues such as population explosion, aging, and chronic diseases are also serious challenges we are currently facing.
&quot;The cooperation between Australia and China in recent years has mainly focused on solving these current problems. &quot;
Marshall said that the International Southern Hemisphere Ocean Research Center, jointly established by CSIRO and the Qingdao National Laboratory of Marine Science and Technology, focuses on observing the El Niño and La Niña phenomena, studying the relationship between them and extreme weather, and establishing the basis for extreme weather Early warning facilities; new cereal varieties jointly developed by CSIRO and the Chinese Academy of Sciences to overcome extreme weather can also alleviate food shortages caused by extreme weather.
&quot;In the current environment, technological innovation is difficult to complete alone, requires extremely high costs, and there are many problems to be solved, so cooperation is particularly important today. &quot;
Marshall said that the closer the cooperation, the more likely it is to achieve breakthrough progress, which is also the significance of Australia and China strengthening cooperation under the &quot;Belt and Road&quot; framework.
&quot;Strengthening bilateral cooperation, for us, is mainly cooperation in science and technology. &quot;
For example, Marshall said that CSIRO has recently developed a gold purification method that does not use cyanide. Because the traditional cyanide gold purification method is very harmful to the environment, many countries hope to find a gold purification method that causes less environmental pollution.
&quot;We are very willing to introduce this technology to China. This is one of the results of our participation in the &#39;Belt and Road&#39; cooperation. &quot;
