North Korean Foreign Minister Ri Yong Ho told the United Nations on Saturday that the continued implementation of sanctions is deepening North Korea&#39;s distrust of the United States and that North Korea cannot unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the United Nations General Assembly that North Korea has adopted &quot;very friendly practices&quot; in the past year, including stopping missile and nuclear tests, dismantling nuclear test sites, and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
&quot;But we have not seen any corresponding response from the United States,&quot; he said.
&quot;If we don&#39;t trust the United States, we have no confidence in our national security. Under such circumstances, we cannot give up our weapons unilaterally first. &quot;
Although Ri Yong Ho repeated North Korea&#39;s complaints about the United States&#39; opposition to &quot;phased&quot; denuclearization, his speech was significant because it did not completely reject unilateral denuclearization as North Korea had done before.
Ri Yong Ho mentioned the joint statement between Kim Jong Un and Trump on June 12. At that time, Kim Jong Un agreed to work towards the &quot;denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula&quot; and Trump promised to protect North Korea&#39;s security.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says it must first give up its nuclear weapons.
The United States has also resisted calls to ease international sanctions on North Korea.
&quot;The United States insists on &#39;denuclearization first,&#39; and increases sanctions and pressure to achieve its goals in a high-pressure manner, even refusing to issue a &#39;declaration of the end of the war,&#39;&quot; Ri Yong-ho said.
