BRUSSELS, Sept 28 (Reuters) - The European Union took a non-confrontational stance on Italy on Friday after Italy defied EU demands and surprised markets with plans for a massive budget deficit, but could take action if Italy insists on too ambitious targets. A more radical position.
Italy&#39;s eurosceptic government is targeting a budget deficit of 2.4% of gross domestic product (GDP) over the next three years, indicating that debt reduction has not been achieved despite demands for deficit reduction.
&quot;We have no interest in a crisis between the Commission and Italy,&quot; Moscovici, the European Commission&#39;s economic affairs commissioner, said on Friday, taking a cautious approach as EU recommendations and sanctions may have little impact on Italy. respond.
EU officials and diplomats remain hopeful that market forces will persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan before it is formally submitted to the European Commission in mid-October.
The euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday and Italian bond yields hit their highest in three weeks after the government announced its plan.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the European Commission may veto Italy&#39;s draft budget, something it has never done with any country.
European Commission Vice President Dombrowski later told a conference in the Latvian capital Riga on Friday that Italy&#39;s current fiscal plan &quot;seems inconsistent with the Stability and Growth Pact,&quot; referring to the EU&#39;s fiscal rules.
But he did not say how this would trigger an EU response.
