Indonesia&#39;s devastated earthquake and tsunami may kill thousands of people - China News Service
According to comprehensive reports, a 7.5-magnitude shallow earthquake occurred in Sulawesi, Indonesia, on September 28, triggering a 6-meter-high tsunami.
The National Disaster Response Department announced on September 30 that the death toll increased to 832, mainly concentrated in the capital Palu and Donggala County, adjacent to the epicenter of the earthquake.
Vice President Kalla pointed out that because casualties have not yet been calculated in some disaster areas, the number of victims may be as high as thousands.
A strong earthquake and tsunami that occurred in Indonesia&#39;s Central Sulawesi province on the afternoon of September 28 has killed 832 people.
Thousands of buildings collapsed, 2.4 million people affected
Palu was devastated after the disaster, with thousands of buildings collapsed and many roads broken. Authorities said an estimated 2.4 million people were affected.
A hotel located along the local coast collapsed. Only 24 guests escaped safely. It is estimated that about 50 to 60 people were trapped in the rubble. Cries for help were heard from time to time at the scene. Rescue workers successfully rescued a young woman on September 30.
Due to the need to ensure the safety of the trapped people, the authorities were unable to use heavy machinery to remove the rubble, and the search and rescue progress was slow.
A shopping mall in the city also collapsed, and hundreds of residents rushed to the scene, waiting for news about relatives and friends.
Many residents used social platforms to post messages in search of lost relatives and friends.
On September 30, local time, a hotel collapsed in Palu, Central Sulawesi, Indonesia, and rescue work was launched.
10,000 people await rescue in Palu, 5 foreigners are missing
Authorities said that about 10,000 people were waiting for rescue in Palu, scattered in 50 locations.
It is reported that there were 71 foreigners in Palu when the earthquake occurred. It is currently known that 66 of them are safe, including 21 Chinese citizens. The whereabouts of the remaining 2 Frenchmen, 2 Malaysian tourists and 1 Korean are unknown.
The Chinese Embassy in Indonesia is using various channels to understand and verify the situation of Chinese citizens in the disaster area. No reports of casualties of Chinese citizens have been received yet.
Communications in Donggala County, which is adjacent to the epicenter of the earthquake, are still interrupted. It is temporarily known that 11 people were killed, but there is no more detailed information.
According to live footage, the coastal areas and ports of Donggala County were severely damaged. A large number of buildings were swept away and bodies were scattered everywhere. The Red Cross rescue team was heading to the local area for search and rescue.
Indonesian President inspects disaster situation and says to start reconstruction work as soon as possible
The roads in Palu and Donggala were severely damaged. On September 30, Palu Airport was only open to aircraft transporting relief supplies, so that rescue supplies and personnel could arrive as soon as possible and the seriously injured could be transported away.
Many local hospitals are still without power, and the injured have to be treated outdoors.
More than 10,000 victims were admitted to shelters. Some people were afraid of going home for fear of aftershocks and preferred to spend the night outdoors.
After a prison in Palu collapsed during the earthquake, causing hundreds of prisoners to escape, more than a hundred prisoners in Donggala County took advantage of the chaos caused by the earthquake to escape, and some prisoners set fire to the detention center to cause trouble.
Indonesian President Joko visited Palu on September 30 to inspect the disaster. He pointed out that it was very difficult to solve a large number of problems in a short period of time, including restoring communications.
He called on the victims to be patient and said the authorities would start reconstruction work as soon as possible.
On the other hand, the Indonesian Finance Minister announced that the government has allocated 560 billion Indonesian rupiah for disaster relief.
One case of human infection with H5N6 avian influenza confirmed in Guangdong Province
The Health Bureau stated that according to the latest notification from the mainland health department, a case of human infection with H5N6 avian influenza was confirmed in Guangdong Province.
The Health Bureau calls on residents to avoid contact with poultry and pay attention to personal and food hygiene.
According to the data, the patient is a 22-year-old male who currently lives in Baiyun District, Guangzhou City, Guangdong Province. He developed fever and other symptoms on September 25 and was admitted to the hospital for treatment on September 26. He is currently being treated in isolation in the hospital and is in critical condition.
The patient had slaughtered and eaten live poultry before becoming ill.
Since April 2014, there have been confirmed cases of H5N6 avian influenza in Sichuan, Guangdong, Yunnan, Hubei, Hunan, Anhui and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
The Health Bureau will continue to maintain close contact with the health departments of the country and neighboring regions and the World Health Organization, and closely monitor the epidemic situation in various places and Macao.
To prevent human infection with avian influenza, the Health Bureau calls on the public to pay attention to the following matters:
Avoid contact with birds or their secretions and excreta; if in contact, wash hands immediately;
Never purchase or carry unquarantine birds;
Do not eat incompletely cooked poultry meat, offal, blood products, eggs, etc.;
Pay attention to personal hygiene and wash hands frequently;
If symptoms such as fever, cough, difficulty breathing, etc. occur, you should wear a mask, seek medical treatment as soon as possible, and provide the doctor with a detailed history of travel and contact with animals.
