The new U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade agreement will preserve U.S. President Donald Trump&#39;s ability to implement his threat to impose 25% tariffs on imported cars, while at the same time reducing passenger car imports from Canada and Mexico, according to ancillary arrangements announced on Monday. Cars, pickup trucks and auto parts are largely exempt from tariffs.
If Trump imposes so-called &quot;Chapter 232&quot; tariffs on cars for national security reasons, Mexico and Canada would each have a quota of 2.6 million duty-free passenger cars exported to the United States each year.
Under the subsidiary arrangement, pickup trucks produced in both countries will be fully exempted from tariffs.
If Trump imposes additional auto tariffs, Mexico will receive an annual tax exemption quota of US$108 billion in auto parts, and Canada will receive a quota of US$32.4 billion.
Both quotas are much higher than the existing production levels of both countries, providing room for growth in exports from both countries.
WASHINGTON/MEXICO, Sept 28 (Reuters) - Mexico said on Friday that U.S. President Donald Trump’s administration and Canada were making real efforts to resolve differences on trade policy after days of wrangling, raising hopes for a new North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA). ) is expected to maintain the form of a tripartite agreement.
