South Korea&#39;s exports fell the most in more than two years in September, but analysts blamed the decline on fewer working days and said global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising trade tensions between China and the United States.
Indeed, South Korea&#39;s average daily exports increased last month.
In addition, preliminary data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first weeks of September before the long holiday.
South Korea&#39;s September exports fell the most year-on-year since July 2016, which was greater than the 5.7% decline expected by 11 analysts polled by Reuters.
Preliminary figures released on Monday showed exports in September at $50.6 billion, down from $51.2 billion in August.
South Korea&#39;s exports to China rose 7.8% in September, expanding for the 23rd consecutive month, despite concerns that the intensifying U.S.-China trade dispute could also harm China&#39;s other export-reliant neighbors.
South Korea&#39;s exports to the United States fell 11.8% due to lower sales of petroleum products.
Overseas sales of South Korea&#39;s memory chips and petroleum products increased by 28.3% and 13.5% respectively, despite market concerns that the so-called chip &quot;super cycle&quot; may have peaked.
&quot;However, the impact of the trade conflict will be difficult to avoid because South Korea&#39;s exports rely heavily on the U.S. and Chinese markets. &quot;
Imports fell 2.1% to US$40.8 billion, which was not as good as the 3.1% growth expected in a Reuters survey.
The preliminary trade surplus in September was US$9.7 billion, up from US$6.9 billion in August.
The Ministry of Industry and Commerce said that thanks to the United States and European Union countries, the global manufacturing industry will remain strong, which is a favorable factor for South Korea&#39;s exports.
The statement pointed out, &quot;The increase in export prices caused by rising oil prices will also be beneficial to exports in the second half of this year. &quot;
&quot;However, the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with the intensification of market volatility after the United States raised interest rates, are all negative pressures faced by exports. &quot;
Exports per working day on average rose to $2.6 billion in September from $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea’s Mid-Autumn Festival falls on September 24-26 this year, so there are only 19.5 working days in September, four days less than the same period last year.
South Korea&#39;s exports from January to September increased by 4.7% compared with the same period last year.
According to the Nikkei/Markit Purchasing Managers&#39; Index, South Korea&#39;s manufacturing activity rebounded in September, but it was supported by domestic orders as orders from China and Japan fell, which may cast a shadow on the export outlook.
