With the approval of Premier Li Keqiang, the State Council recently issued the &quot;Decision on Further Reducing the Catalog of Industrial Product Production License Management and Simplifying the Approval Procedures.&quot;
The &quot;Decision&quot; proposes to further reduce the management catalog of industrial product production licenses, cancel the management of production licenses for 14 categories of industrial products, and delegate the management authority of production licenses for four categories of industrial products to the quality and technical supervision departments of provincial people&#39;s governments.
After this reform, the products subject to industrial product production license management will be reduced from 38 categories last year to the current 24 categories.
The &quot;Decision&quot; clearly states that simplified approval procedures will be implemented for products in the catalog.
The first is to change the pre-certification product inspection organized by the licensing authority to a product inspection report issued by a qualified inspection and testing agency when the enterprise applies.
Second, in addition to hazardous chemicals, post-on-site review will be implemented for products licensed by the quality and technical supervision department (market supervision and management department) of the provincial people&#39;s government. After the enterprise submits the application and product inspection report and makes a commitment to ensure product quality and safety , you can receive a production license after passing the formal examination, and then undergo on-site inspection within the specified time.
Third, if an enterprise produces products of different categories in its business catalog, in accordance with the principle of &quot;one enterprise, one license&quot;, when applying for a new license or applying for a license renewal, one license will be reviewed and issued together.
The &quot;Decision&quot; requires that all regions and relevant departments must solidly advance the work of reducing the catalog and simplifying the approval procedures.
Strengthen the disclosure of enterprise commitments and post-on-site inspections, strengthen credit supervision and restraint measures, implement the main responsibility of enterprise quality, and revoke production licenses for false promises and non-compliance with requirements.
For products whose industrial product production license management has been cancelled, it is necessary to effectively strengthen interim and ex-post supervision. Products involving public health and safety, environmental protection and other products can be converted to compulsory certification. A positive list should be made public and disclosed to the public. Certification standards should be unified and reasonable. Certification and testing projects will be reduced and merged, and compulsory certification fees will in principle be borne by finance at all levels according to the system.
Take support measures to encourage enterprises to carry out voluntary certification, promote brand building and expand markets.
It is necessary to benchmark against advanced international standards and promote the improvement of industrial product quality.
Give full play to the role of third-party social organizations to ensure the quality and safety of industrial products.
For products that retain industrial product production license management, it is necessary to improve the standard system, give full play to the advantages of industry supervision, strengthen the responsibility of &quot;whoever approves, who supervises&quot;, dynamically assess product quality and safety risks, reduce the catalog, delegate approval authority, or convert to certification in a timely manner. manage.
In September, China&#39;s comprehensive PMI increased month-on-month and the manufacturing PMI fell month-on-month.
Data released by the National Bureau of Statistics of China on the 30th showed that in September, China&#39;s comprehensive PMI output index was 54.1%, which was 0.3 and 0.1 percentage points higher than the previous month and the annual average, indicating that the production and operation activities of Chinese enterprises have generally remained stable.
In that month, the manufacturing production index and non-manufacturing business activity index, which constitute the comprehensive PMI output index, were 53.0% and 54.9% respectively, falling and rising month-on-month.
Among them, China&#39;s manufacturing PMI was 50.8%, down 0.5 percentage points from the previous month.
Zhao Qinghe said that this month’s manufacturing PMI has five main characteristics:
First, the fundamentals of the manufacturing industry are generally stable.
Among the 21 industries surveyed, the PMI of 14 industries is in the expansion range. Among them, the PMI of manufacturing industries such as medicine, special equipment, and electrical machinery and equipment are all at a relatively high operating level of above 53.5%, with rapid growth.
Second, supply and demand fluctuated slightly.
The production index and new order index were 53.0% and 52.0%, down 0.3 and 0.2 percentage points respectively from the previous month. Supply and demand continued to remain prosperous, but the expansion slowed down slightly.
The new export order index and import index were 48.0% and 48.5%, 1.4 and 0.6 percentage points lower than last month respectively, and the prosperity level both fell to the low of the year.
Fourth, the cost of purchasing raw materials for enterprises has increased.
The purchase price index of main raw materials was 59.8%, an increase of 1.1 percentage points from the previous month, and the ex-factory price index was 54.3%, the same as the previous month, both of which were highs during the year.
Fifth, large enterprises are operating steadily, and the operating conditions of small enterprises continue to improve.
The PMI of large enterprises was 52.1%, the same as last month. Since the beginning of this year, the index has always been in the expansion range of 52.0% and above, and the production index and new orders index have increased month-on-month this month, which is the main driving force for the manufacturing industry to maintain expansion; The PMI of medium-sized enterprises was 48.7%, 1.7 percentage points lower than the previous month, and was in the contraction range; the PMI of small enterprises was 50.4%, 0.4 percentage points higher than the previous month, rising for two consecutive months.
That month, China&#39;s non-manufacturing business activity index was 54.9%, an increase of 0.7 percentage points from the previous month and rising for two consecutive months.
Zhao Qinghe believes that the non-manufacturing industry as a whole continues to maintain a steady and positive development momentum.
The business activity index of road transportation, securities, real estate and other industries continues to be below the critical point, and the total business volume has decreased.
NAGOYA, Nov 5 (Reuters) - Bank of Japan Governor Haruhiko Kuroda said on Monday that the central bank is aware that long-term implementation of ultra-loose monetary policy could squeeze the profit margins of financial institutions and potentially destabilize the country&#39;s banking system.
But he said the BOJ needed to maintain its massive stimulus program while keeping a close eye on the pros and cons of its policies, given sluggish inflation and uncertainty in overseas economies.
&quot;The Bank of Japan fully acknowledges that under continued monetary easing, the strength of financial institutions will be increasingly affected,&quot; Kuroda said in a speech to business leaders in Nagoya.
He said that if financial institutions take on risks more actively to make up for the impact of narrow profit margins caused by low interest rates for many years, the banking system may be destabilized in the event of a serious negative shock.
&quot;Although these risks are not significant at present, the central bank will pay close attention to the development of the situation and encourage financial institutions to take necessary measures,&quot; he said.
Minutes of the Bank of Japan meeting released earlier on Monday showed that at the September interest rate meeting, the Bank of Japan&#39;s policy committee discussed the rising costs of long-term easing policy.
Minutes of the meeting showed that one member said that if the economy continues to expand, &quot;the Bank of Japan will have more room for flexibility in policy in the future.&quot;
Minutes of the meeting showed another member said the committee should discuss how long the BOJ can maintain its stimulus policy, given that there are limits to the duration of the policy.
Haruhiko Kuroda said that the Bank of Japan will evaluate the financial risks caused by its loose policy and also need to consider the uncertainty surrounding Japan&#39;s economic outlook, as Sino-US trade friction and rising protectionism may affect global demand.
&quot;The impact of such problems on Japan&#39;s economy is limited for the time being,&quot; Kuroda said.
&quot;But if the problem persists, the impact on Japan&#39;s economy may become greater,&quot; he added.
&quot;There is a need to continue strong monetary easing while taking into account the positive and negative impacts in a balanced way,&quot; Kuroda said.
Although the disadvantages of the aggressive stimulus plan have increased, such as long-term low interest rates eroding the profits of financial institutions, low inflation has forced the Bank of Japan to maintain the plan.
The Bank of Japan maintained its monetary policy last month; facing risks from a global trade war, Haruhiko Kuroda ruled out the possibility of raising interest rates in the near future.
June 1, 2018, Cardiff, USA, the corporate logo on a Tesla electric vehicle.
According to a settlement agreement, Tesla Motors and its CEO Musk have each agreed to pay a $20 million fine to financial regulators. Musk will also resign as chairman of the company but remains CEO.
The settlement would cap two months of turmoil at Tesla.
The settlement of securities fraud charges disclosed by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission on Saturday will bring relief to investors.
Investors had worried that a protracted legal battle would only further damage the electric car company, which still loses money.
The SEC sued Musk for fraud on Thursday, saying his August 7 tweets misled investors.
He tweeted that he was considering taking Tesla private at $420 per share and had received financing.
The SEC said these tweets were actually unfounded and the market turmoil they caused harmed investors.
Investors and corporate governance experts said the agreement could strengthen Tesla, which has been hit hard by Musk&#39;s recent behavior.
Steven Heim, head of Boston Common Asset Management, said the settlement should bring more oversight to Musk without taking &quot;devastating&quot; steps to oust him from Tesla.
The asset manager owns shares of Tesla&#39;s battery maker Panasonic.
Under the proposed deal, Tesla must appoint an independent chairman, two independent directors and a board committee to develop controls over Musk&#39;s external communications.
&quot;It is in the best interest of our markets and our investors, including Tesla shareholders, that this matter be resolved expeditiously and on the terms agreed upon,&quot; SEC Chairman Clayton said in a statement.
Thursday&#39;s accusations wiped about $7 billion from Tesla&#39;s market value, which was valued at $45.2 billion on Friday, below General Motors&#39; $47.5 billion.
In the settlement agreement, the SEC withdrew its request to oust Musk from the company&#39;s leadership.
