All 46 types of supervision certificates in Inner Mongolia’s import and export links have been verified online - China News Service
China News Service, Hohhot, November 5 (Reporter Li Aiping) Hohhot Customs reported on the 5th that from now on, except for special circumstances such as confidentiality requirements, all 46 types of local import and export supervision certificates will be verified online.
Inner Mongolia companies can use a paperless method to declare relevant documents to the customs, avoiding the previous problems of on-site travel, paper applications, and repeated submissions.
It is understood that document preparation time refers to the preparation time for various documents required for import and export before customs declaration. It is a major factor affecting the overall customs clearance time. In order to shorten customs clearance time and reduce customs clearance fees, documents must be reduced. .
Previously, there were 86 types of regulatory documents that required customs verification during the import and export process, involving 19 departments.
It is reported that this time, in accordance with the principle of &quot;cancellation of what can be canceled, merger of what can be merged, exit of port verification of what can be withdrawn&quot;, relying on the &quot;single window&quot; platform for international trade, the customs system docked and Data interconnection enables data to travel more and enterprises to travel less.
Customs said that in the past, companies had to go back and forth to the on-site service halls of relevant departments to submit paper applications. The process was long and the review status could not be tracked in real time.
Now business users can directly log in to the &quot;single window&quot; portal and apply online.
After the certificate issuance department passes the review, the electronic data of the certificate will be transmitted to the customs, and automatic comparison with the customs declaration data and intelligent verification will be realized during the customs clearance process. The review results will be fed back to the enterprise through a &quot;single window&quot;, realizing the declaration of regulatory certificates. The entire process of review, customs clearance and feedback is handled online.
Exports of Korean ginseng chicken soup to China surged 20 times in four years, which may be related to the increase in empty-nest youth - China News Service
Exports of Korean ginseng chicken soup to China surged 20 times in 4 years Analysis: Related to the increase in empty-nest youth
Yonhap News Agency reported on the 5th that South Korean ginseng chicken soup exports to China exceeded US$100,000 last year, a surge of about 20 times compared with 2013, four years ago.
Analysts believe that this growth is related to the increasing number of empty-nest young people in China, which has led to the hot sales of convenience foods, as well as the increasing attention of young people to nutritious meals.
The data was released by the Korea Agriculture, Fisheries and Food Trade Corporation (aT) on the 5th.
Last year, the export volume of Korean ginseng chicken soup to China reached US$100,339, and the weight reached 21,859 kilograms, a surge of 2094% and 3668.8% respectively compared with 2013.
Analysts believe that the increase in sales of Korean ginseng chicken soup in China is related to the increase in empty-nest youth, which has driven the sales of convenience foods, and to the increased attention of young people to nutritious meals.
As of this year, the number of one-person households in China has exceeded 200 million, and is expected to increase to 30% of the total population in 2020. Local food companies have also launched various convenience foods targeting &quot;single eaters&quot;.
In addition, the analysis also showed that bird flu is the biggest factor preventing ginseng chicken soup from taking root in the mainland Chinese market.
aT said that an avian influenza epidemic occurred in South Korea from November 2016 to April last year, and relevant departments completely banned the export of ginseng chicken soup to China, resulting in a sharp drop in exports.
In 2016, the export value of ginseng chicken soup to China reached US$840,000. Due to avian influenza, the export value plummeted to US$100,000 last year.
