During the 73rd session of the United Nations General Assembly, all parties released some positive messages on the Korean Peninsula issue.
South Korean President Moon Jae-in relayed North Korea&#39;s &quot;irreversible&quot; determination to denuclearize and said that US President Trump and North Korean leader Kim Jong-un may meet before the end of this year.
The U.S. State Department subsequently stated that Secretary of State Pompeo will visit North Korea in October to promote the implementation of the commitments of the Singapore meeting between the leaders of the United States and North Korea.
Since the beginning of this year, North Korea and South Korea have broken the ice and opened up the path to dialogue. Leaders of North Korea, South Korea, and the United States have held meetings. The general trend of easing the situation on the peninsula has continued, and the principle of resolving peninsula issues through dialogue has also been adhered to.
First of all, &quot;the essence of the peninsula issue is a security issue&quot; has not changed. The key to achieving peace on the peninsula is to properly and balancedly resolve the reasonable security concerns of all parties, rather than blindly putting pressure on the other side and blindly emphasizing one&#39;s own demands.
Secondly, in the dialogue to achieve denuclearization of the peninsula, the relevant parties still have differences on the steps and methods to achieve denuclearization of the peninsula. Due to the long-term lack of political trust between North Korea and the United States, the game mentality of &quot;who comes first and who comes last&quot; is still strong.
At the Security Council&#39;s public meeting on the Korean Peninsula issue held at the United Nations Headquarters in New York a few days ago, the different voices from all parties around the issue of sanctions against North Korea once again highlighted that these two points on the Peninsula issue have &quot;not changed.&quot;
U.S. Secretary of State Pompeo insists that sanctions against North Korea will not be lifted until the Korean peninsula is completely denuclearized.
Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov emphasized the principle of &quot;responding to action with action.&quot; He pointed out: &quot;The weakening trend of sanctions should be in sync with North Korea&#39;s steps on the road to gradually denuclearization.&quot;
There is no doubt that relevant parties should continue to fully, completely and accurately implement the Security Council&#39;s resolutions related to North Korea, but pressure is not the purpose. Implementing sanctions and promoting political settlement are both requirements of the Security Council resolutions. One cannot be partial to the other, and one cannot choose only one. .
As Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi said, in view of the current positive progress in relations between North Korea, South Korea and the United States, China believes that it is necessary for the Security Council to consider activating reversible provisions at an appropriate time, thereby encouraging North Korea and relevant parties to take greater steps in the direction of denuclearization. pace of.
Looking back on the past, every progress in the denuclearization and peace process of the peninsula required sufficient political courage from all parties.
At present, in the face of the international community&#39;s increasing expectations for the political settlement of the Peninsula issue, relevant parties should especially demonstrate political courage, make political decisions, implement commitments, resolve problems, continue to take steps toward each other, and advance the Peninsula issue in parallel. The denuclearization process and the establishment of a peace mechanism on the peninsula will jointly create permanent peace on the peninsula.
