TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence among Japan&#39;s largest manufacturers hit its lowest level in more than a year in the September quarter, the Bank of Japan&#39;s quarterly Tankan survey showed on Monday, as rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affected production. Businesses are feeling the pinch.
The survey showed little evidence that escalating global trade frictions have dampened confidence among large manufacturers.
However, the risk of a full-scale trade war has hit corporate business prospects and may threaten corporate capital expenditures.
Buoyant capital spending is a bright spot in Japan&#39;s economy.
The survey casts doubt on the Bank of Japan&#39;s view that solid economic expansion will help accelerate inflation towards its 2% target, despite signs that companies are gradually passing costs on to customers.
&quot;Confidence among manufacturers has stagnated due to slowing exports and weak factory production amid concerns over the global trade war,&quot; said Takeshi Minami, chief researcher at Norinchukin Research Institute.
&quot;Confidence remains high. And because corporate profits are improving and prices are rising, I don&#39;t think confidence will continue to decline. &quot;
The Tankan survey showed that the judgment index on the prosperity of large-scale manufacturing industries fell to positive 19 in September from positive 21 three months ago, which was the third consecutive quarter of deterioration.
The market&#39;s median estimate was positive 22.
The sentiment judgment index for the large non-manufacturing industry fell to positive 22 in September from positive 24 in the June survey, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
The Reuters survey was positive at 22.
The survey shows that both the large-scale manufacturing and non-manufacturing business climate judgment indexes are expected to remain unchanged in December.
Investors were unfazed by the decline in the Tankan&#39;s business sentiment index, with Japan&#39;s Nikkei index rising to a 27-year high on Monday as the yen&#39;s continued depreciation helped improve Japanese companies&#39; export profit prospects.
Capital expenditures are solid.
Although business confidence fell, the latest Tankan highlighted solid corporate capital spending plans, helped by renewed capacity and increased investment in robots and automation to cope with labor shortages caused by an aging population.
The central bank&#39;s Tankan survey shows that large companies plan to increase capital expenditures by 13.4% in the current fiscal year ending in March 2019.
It was 13.6% in the previous Tankan survey.
Minami Takeshi said that capital expenditures of all enterprises this fiscal year are planned to increase by 8.5%, which is close to the pace of Japan&#39;s bubble economy era.
&quot;With small businesses raising their profit forecasts from now on, there is still room for further growth in capital spending, but much depends on the impact of the trade war on business confidence,&quot; he said.
The Tankan survey showed that companies&#39; ability to pass on costs has increased. The output price index of large companies was positive 7, the highest point in ten years. This is an encouraging sign and reflects the progress made in Japan&#39;s efforts to fight deflation.
The index measuring the employment status of large enterprises hit minus 23, the tightest level since 1992, highlighting the tightening of the job market.
Japan&#39;s economy rebounded in the second quarter from a contraction in January-March this year, thanks to strong business spending.
However, trade frictions escalated in the summer and supply chains were disrupted by natural disasters, clouding the outlook for Japan&#39;s export-reliant economy.
