Beijing, November 5 (Reuters) - A press release issued by the China Foreign Trade Center on Sunday stated that the Canton Fair showed that China&#39;s foreign trade situation remains complex and severe, with 80.6% of companies expecting exports in 2018 to be better than the previous year or remain the same.
However, considering the external environment in which the cost of domestic raw materials, labor and other comprehensive factors continues to rise, and the impact of Sino-US trade friction is increasing, exhibitors also believe that the export situation next year is not optimistic.
At the closing press conference of the 124th Canton Fair, Xu Bing, Deputy Secretary-General, Spokesperson and Deputy Director of the China Foreign Trade Center, said that the number of overseas buyers attending this Canton Fair and the export transactions both decreased slightly year-on-year.
There were 189,812 buyers attending the conference this year, coming from 215 countries and regions, a year-on-year decrease of 1.11%.
Export transactions were RMB 206.494 billion (equivalent to US$29.86 billion), a year-on-year decrease of 1%.
From a market perspective, transactions with Japan, the ten ASEAN countries, the BRIC countries, and South Korea increased by 74.4%, 11.4%, 7.2%, and 2.5% respectively, while transactions with traditional markets such as the United States, Australia, Canada, and the European Union decreased by 30.3%, and 8.9% respectively. %, 7.3%, 0.8%.
From an industry perspective, transportation, machinery and equipment, construction and decoration materials, consumer electronics and information products, and bathroom equipment increased by 24.8%, 21.1%, 20.0%, 15.1%, and 7.6% respectively, while textiles and clothing, and household appliances decreased by 13.0% respectively. , 6.7%.
Xu Bing said that as a barometer and weather vane of China&#39;s foreign trade, the buyer attendance situation and export transaction data of this Canton Fair show that China&#39;s foreign trade development next year will still face many uncertain and unstable factors.
However, with the deepening of supply-side structural reform, and the recent national and local policies and measures on &quot;six stability&quot; and other aspects, China&#39;s foreign trade development is accelerating the accumulation of new momentum, and corporate market diversification continues to make new progress. These They are all important foundations and powerful conditions for the development of foreign trade.
&quot;Taking all factors into consideration, it is expected that China&#39;s foreign trade import and export will maintain steady growth throughout the year, with quality and efficiency further improved.&quot; Xu Bing said.
The General Administration of Customs of China announced that exports in US dollar terms increased by 14.5% year-on-year in September, and imports increased by 14.3% year-on-year. The trade surplus in September was US$31.69 billion. Both the export growth rate and the trade surplus in September were the highest since February this year.
Despite the escalating trade friction between China and the United States, China&#39;s export performance in September still significantly exceeded expectations. Strong external demand, companies rushing to export before the United States imposes additional tariffs, and the depreciation of the RMB exchange rate are the main supporting factors, which also show the resilience of China&#39;s foreign trade to a certain extent. , but the impact of the Sino-US trade war on confidence and the industrial chain cannot be underestimated. Analysts believe that the challenges of China&#39;s foreign trade may appear in the fourth quarter or next year.
A Reuters survey showed that U.S. fund managers recommended increasing their cash holdings in September and continued to maintain a cautious stance as the United States and China began the latest round of mutual import tariffs and the dispute showed no signs of easing.
However, according to the recommendations of the 12 fund managers who participated in this survey, asset allocation in North America increased to the highest level since June 2017, while positions in the United Kingdom, the Eurozone, and especially emerging markets declined.
The global stock allocation averaged 56.6% and bonds accounted for 35.5%, basically consistent with last month&#39;s survey.
