More than 90% of Brazilian female voters said that presidential candidates did not consider the needs of women.
According to the South American Overseas Chinese News Network, data recently released by the Brazilian National Geographic Institute (IBGE) shows that more than 90% of Brazilian women do not believe that presidential candidates consider the needs of women.
According to the report, currently, the number of women in Brazil has reached 107 million. If all the women in Brazil were gathered together to form a country, the country&#39;s population would rank 13th in the world, with a population that is more than twice the population of Spain.
In Brazil, female voters account for 52% of the total voters, and men account for 48%. Although the proportion of women among voters is very high, in Brazil&#39;s Congress, women only account for 10%.
Among 193 countries in the world, Brazilian women&#39;s participation in politics ranks only 154th, higher than Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of struggle for rights, Brazilian women still have not succeeded in obtaining the rights they deserve.
Brazilian sociologist Natalia Mori pointed out that the reason for this phenomenon is the result of the interaction of ancient patriarchal society, racism and capitalist values.
&quot;Politics should be about citizens claiming civil rights, identity, access to public goods, and multiple social groups forming the same society. But politics in Brazil is a monopoly of one group, and the majority of the population is not represented. &quot;
A previous study conducted by the Brazilian Motorcycle Research Institute (Locomotiva) also pointed out that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that elected politicians can represent their rights, and 90% of Brazilian women disagree with the decisions made by politicians. , 93% of women disagree with the current government policies.
&quot;We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament. Brazil&#39;s political system is still affected by inequality. So far, there are still serious gender, class and racial discrimination in Brazilian politics.&quot; Natalia・Morrie said.
Despite women&#39;s lack of rights, most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
The survey shows that 76% of women believe that they can make a difference in democratic elections, and 72% of women are interested in politics.
In addition, 55% of women believe that democratic politics is the best way to make women suffer less prejudice.
