Systemic lupus erythematosus is a chronic and difficult disease that affects multiple organs throughout the body. It was once considered an &quot;incurable disease&quot;.
Because its pathogenesis is unclear, diagnosis and treatment are difficult, and effective treatments are lacking, it cannot be cured.
Recently, a team led by Liu Wanli, a researcher at the School of Life Sciences at Tsinghua University, and Li Zhangguo, director of the Rheumatology and Immunology Center at Peking University People&#39;s Hospital, discovered that human immunoglobulins have molecular variations that increase susceptibility to systemic lupus erythematosus, and that this variation is involved in the regulation of immune B cells. .
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the human body is an important cause of systemic lupus erythematosus.
According to Sun Xiaolin, one of the authors of the article and Peking University People&#39;s Hospital, Li Zhanguo&#39;s team collected nearly 2,000 large samples of systemic lupus erythematosus patients and conducted research. They found that patients with immunoglobulin mutations produced pathogenic cells in a wide variety and quantity. With more autoantibodies, the incidence and severity of inflammation such as nephritis, arthritis, serositis, and vasculitis are significantly increased.
Through various research methods such as immune cell tracing, animal experiments, and sequencing, Liu Wanli&#39;s team discovered the immune signaling pathway activated by this immune molecule mutation and the pathogenic mechanism that promotes B cells to secrete a variety of autoantibodies.
The reporter learned that the two teams have joined forces to give full play to their respective advantages and achieve a close integration of basic research and clinical application.
Liu Wanli&#39;s team is committed to research on B lymphocyte immune recognition and immune activation, while Li Zhanguo&#39;s team has been engaged in clinical research on systemic lupus erythematosus for a long time.
&quot;This study is one of the results of many years of cooperation between the two teams. It is also the first time that the academic community has recognized that immunoglobulin gene abnormalities will induce systemic lupus erythematosus on a mechanistic basis, laying a solid foundation for further academic research and clinical targeted therapy. Base. &quot;
