The results of the Okinawa governor election, which was held in advance due to the death of former governor Onaga Yushi from illness, were announced in the early morning of the 1st local time. Tamaki Danny, who opposed the relocation plan of the US military base in Japan, was successfully elected.
The election was counted on September 30. The final results showed that Tamaki received a total of 396,632 votes, the most votes in the history of the Okinawa Prefecture governor election, and more than 80,000 votes more than his main opponent Masaki Saki.
A total of 4 candidates participated in this election, and the voting rate was 63.24%, which was 0.89 percentage points lower than the 2014 Okinawa Prefecture governor election.
Tamaki told the media on the 1st that the election results showed that the people of the county did not want Governor Onaga’s lifetime efforts to be in vain. He will inherit Governor Onaga’s legacy and continue to oppose the US military base relocation plan and the closure of Futenma base to the Japanese and U.S. governments. make an effort.
The Futenma US military base is located in Ginowan City, Okinawa Prefecture. It has been criticized for a long time. The Japanese and US governments previously agreed to relocate it to the Henoko area of Nago City. However, the people of Okinawa strongly opposed it and hoped that the base could be completely moved out of Okinawa. .
As for the relocation plan that prefectural residents strongly oppose and the request to revoke the Henoko coastal reclamation permit, Tamaki said that he did not take an antagonistic or divisive position with the central government at the beginning, and hoped that the two sides could fully exchange views and show that intention to resolve through negotiation.
Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe also told the media on the morning of the 1st that he seriously accepted the result and would make efforts to revitalize Okinawa and reduce the burden on the base.
