Since the mid-2000s, North Dakota farmer Paul Thomas has been planting more and more soybeans on his land as China&#39;s demand for the oilseed grows.
This transformation reached its peak this year, when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres, reaching an unprecedented scale.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch to corn and wheat in 2019, which have been staple crops in America’s agricultural regions.
U.S. farmers planted more soybeans than corn this year for the first time in 35 years.
The plan to switch to other food crops is because U.S. farmers are facing difficulties selling soybeans in the context of U.S. President Trump&#39;s trade war with China.
China normally buys about 60% of U.S. soybean exports, but has purchased almost zero U.S. soybeans in recent months because of the trade war, sending soybean prices to a decade low.
Thomas plans to grow more wheat next year, hoping to make more money by reducing his reliance on crops that depend on demand from China.
Thomas said soybean prices &quot;hit us hard.&quot;
He said that without Chinese buying demand, the spot price of soybeans near his farm is US$7.10 per bushel, and the price necessary to cover costs is US$8.50.
U.S. farmers have planted soybean acreage at a record high this year, and the harvest is also expected to hit a record high.
At such a vulnerable moment, they were hit by the trade war.
In response to Trump&#39;s tariffs on imported Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on U.S. soybeans in July.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture will release its first estimate of planted acreage next year, which is expected to include consideration of the impact of tariffs.
The forecast is expected to confirm private sector expectations that soybean acreage will decrease.
Informa Economics forecast on Oct. 19 that the area planted to corn will increase 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) in 2019, while the area planted to soybeans will decrease 7% to 83 million acres, according to a report seen by Reuters.
Informa also expects U.S. wheat acreage to increase by 4%.
The area of soybeans planted before the retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, about 15 million acres more than a decade ago.
Corn acreage has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres, and wheat acreage this year is 47.8 million acres, close to the lowest level in 100 years.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Growers Association, has a total planting area of 3,600 acres. This year, he planted nearly half of soybeans, but plans to cut back in the future.
He said he might increase corn acreage by up to 20% on his farm in northern Illinois, the largest soybean-growing state in the United States.
Soybeans yield less per acre than corn, but they also require less fertilizer, making soybeans less expensive to grow overall.
If farmers switch to final-value corn, it could raise costs but benefit some companies, including fertilizer seller Andersons Inc.
Andersons chief executive Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected the switch to corn would benefit fertilizer use.
Bayer also expects to benefit from farmers switching to corn.
